U .*6\nCuticura Soap\nIs Ideal for\nThe Complexion\nZ?\nModern Fireproof Storage\nt'l T\"K t l'\nlaij\nSAVE lldNET \"Sjf\nTOfE. WORRT m U>CAL ANDSM\nlongdistance moving\n.j** \"..MqiiiB. shipping.\nlswed f?r *2.000 wku. u ?it\nNwg-dWtaaee eaas; ISM mm la< fee T<?r\njflffcLOANS\nI HORNING\nDiuiondi, Watches, Jewelry\nj Sooth End of Highway Bridge\nBroken\nTrunks\nrepaired promptly\nCafl Fraakfia\n4856\ntdphaits\n(No Branchca)\n80 l St. n. e.\n(Established 18)5)\nJT*U1?^|AD^00RDEJ\nDANCE\nT~ C?M Leers at tie\nItfliftriy School tf Ducty\nMi* Maw lark Ave.\ni\nSpecial for ladies I\nSUITS, UhsM*\n[.H. PIE^rw. 1838 H Street W. W.\nPRUSSIANS EVINCE\nSCANTY INTEREST\nON ELECTION DAY\nBernstorff Opposed Because\nBritish Might Object\nto Americanism.\nBERLIN. Feb. JO.?-Prussia is goInf\nthrough the flrat test of Its\ndemocracy today In the election S>I\nthe first regular Prussian parliament\nunder the republican government.\nThe new parliament Is to\nreplace the provisional constitutional\nassembly.\nThe flrst regular election la expected\nto show that the new republican\neoat of state does not tit the\npeople comfortably. General predictions\nIncline to the belief that there\nwill be a shift to the right with\nconsiderable conservative gains and\na cutting down of the Social Democratic\nmembership in parliament.\nThe election corresponds to tha\nState elections in America, more\nparticularly like New York, at ai\nNew York would be If It was an\noverwhelmingly dominant State and\nruhning the country as Prussia\nruns Germany.\nFrom the extreme radicals to th<\nreactionary elements there is bittei\ncomplaint of the apathy and indifference\nof the people. In fact the)\ntake so little Interest compared tc\nthe Interest In an American electlor\nday. that so far the campaign hat\nbeen extremely tame. Efforts art\nbeing made ,today by the different\nparties to get out the voters and\nbut for the fact that the electlor\nIs held on Sunday a much smallei\npercentage would go to the polls.\nWaawa Uninterested.\nWomen, upon whom suffrage vat\nthrust by the revolution? evinced a\nrelatively small Interest in the campaign.\nThat the Prussian masses\ndo not yet thoroughly understand\ntheir new system and feel strangely\ntoward It t? plainly evident on\nevery hand.\nThe campaign is practically without\nany real Issues. The extreme\nradicals want Communism and alliance\nwith Russia. The Social\nDemocrats, whose passive negative\npolicy would turn Germany Into a\npaciflctic European China, have\ntried to scare the voters with the\ndanger of the return of the Hoiensoliems\nIf the Conservatives regain\ncontrol of Prussia.\nThe conservative monarchists\nGerman peoples and the German\nnational parties have laid chief\nphasis on the demoralization dne to\nstrikes and on profiteering and\ngraft as well as corruption and Incapacity\namong the officials of Germany\nsince the revolution as the\nbest proof of what Germany would\nbe under a Social Democratic\nregime.\nThe Democratic party, which lost\nthe heaviest of all the parties in\nthe Reichstag elections, is expected\nto lose a proportionately heavy vote\ntoday. The utter lack of national\nspirit is one of the chief charges\nagainst that party.\nBernstorff. running as a Democrat\nin Schleswlg in a by-election.\nIs believed to have a good chance\nof election to the Reichstag. Hia\nopenly avowed pro Americanism\nhas made him many enemies every\ntime his name came up for a ministerial\npost, the final argument\nagainst him always being that England\nwould not stand for him in the\ngovernment.\nLEGION FORMS\nFOREIGN POSTS\nV _______\nINDIANAPOLIS. Ind.. Feb. 20.?\nFifty-one posts of the American Legion\nhave beep chartered outside\nthe continental limits of the United\nStates, according to national head*\nquarters here. The posts are distributed\namong three territorial\npossessions and seventeen foreign\ncountries of four continents.\nAlaska leads the list with posts\nat Anchorage. Valdez. Ketchikan.\nJuneau. Seward. Wrangell. Fort LIscum.\nCordova. Nome. Haines. Fairbanks.\nSitka and Petersburg. The\nfollowing Hawaiian cities have\nposts: Honolulu. Kealla. Hilo. Kapaau.\nWalalua. Schodeid Barracks.\nFort Kamehameha and Kahulul\nThe legion Is organized in the Philippines\nat Manila. Cuartel de Espana.\nCavlte. Fort William, MCKinley\nand Corregidor.\nForeign posts have been formed\nat Buenos Ayres. Argentina; Brussels,\nBelgium; Rio de Janeiro, Brazil:\nMontreal, Canada; Chuqufcamata.\nChile; Shanghai and Pekln.\nChina: Havana. Cuba: London. England:\nGuatemala City, Guatemala;\nParis, La Rochelle\" and Gievres\nFrance; Coblentz, Germany; Tokyo\nYokohama and Kobe, Japan; Mexico\nCity and Tampico. Mexico; Cerrc\nde Pasco. Peru; Balboa. Cristoba'\nand Gatun. Panama: Warsaw. Poland;\nand S|nto Domingo. Dominican\nRepublic.\nDe not he despondent aknli\nyear ease be proaoaaeed laearable.\ntear wta were werae than yea\nare aew eajeylag good health\ntfter try lag CHIROPRACTIC.\nBring this ad te mr, Ita valae la\nfts.ftft\nDR. W. F. MARVEL\nPope Bldg., 817 14th St. N. W.\nFrank. i334-J.\nN,\ndoes a aa\nthe hearts\nFoe 18\nthe pnblie\ntiatrjr. It\nI Ouirutt\nWi/ BOW\npoeal X-n\nvanio lonli\ntioa, Oana\nthe paia.\nTerm* o\nPrfe.\nMY F\nDcStkuil\nIt Lr- e .....a.\nOFFICIAL TEXT L\nCLAIM TO YAP\nAFTER STUDY\nSecret Data Shows A\nCase, Correijx\nBy CARL, W. ACJKBRXAH.\n(BpeeUl OeWa H?tM U\nIk* TuUuUd HaraM.)\nLONDON. Feb. JO?The future of\nthe Island of Yap ha* been settled.\nI was Informed today by the very\nhighest authority that Japan's\nclaims to this former German Island\nIn the Pacific have been substantiated\nby the only olBclal report of\nthis aspect of the peace conference\nin Parts, which is now and has\nbeen In the keeping of Sir Maurice\nHankey. one of LJoyd George's pri'\nvmte secretaries.\nAfter a full lrtve?tlBatlon of I\nPresident Wilson's contention that\nTap was excepted from the ..general\nagreement of the powers at Paris\nand that the Japanese mandate does\n1 not ?pply to this Island, an Investt1\nnation which I made personally In\n1 Feme. Paris and London, I learned\n1 that the only official transcript of\n1 the minutes of this session of the\nSupreme Council wa*. by agreement\nPLANS SURPRISE\ni IN HATFIELD CASE\nt\nState to Train Big Guns on\nDefense During Mingo\nTrial.\nI 0\nWILLIAMSON. W. VA. Feb. 20\nThe prosecution is expected to Are\nif a big guns during the comiug\nweek in the trial of Sid Hatfield\nand eighteen others charged with\nthe murder of Albert Felts.\nCounsel for the State was author[\nity for the statements tonight that\nl a number of men not Indicted?be,\ncause evidence against them was\nnot produced before the grand\nJury?should have been made co,\ndefendants because of their connection\nwith the alleged conspiracy.\nThe belief was expressed that\nfurther indictments in the Matewan\nt murder case will follow.\nTe Ac^alt One.\nWhen the Commonwealth of West\nVirginia presents its case to the\nJury It will ask for a verdict of\nacquittal for one of the nineteen accused.\nThe original Intention was\nto nolle the indictment against this\ndefendant, but the moment the Jury\nwas sworn and his life placed in\njeopardy that course became lm\npossible. The State will tell the\nJurors that it has been unable to\nconnect this man with the gun battle\nat Matewan. May 19. last, which\ncost the lives of seven Baldwin\nFelts detectives and three Matewan\ncitizens. In asserting its intention\nof proving a conspiracy on the part\nof the defendants the prose<*ution\nemphasized that such a crime can j\nbe proved by circumstantial evi-1\ndence as well a?* by direct proof.\nThe correspondent learned tonight\nthat the State expects to produce\nwitnesses who saw the following\nmen shoot at the Baldwin- I\nFelts detectives:\nSid Hatfield. Bowser Coleman\n\"Doug* Mounts. Van Clay, William\nBowman, Reese Chambers, Clare\ni Overstreet. Jim Overstreet. Jesse\nBoyd. Fred Burgraff and Art Williams.\nResentment over the evictions of\nunion miners and their families hy\nI Felts detectives will be laid down\nby the State as the basic motiv# of I\nthe alleged conspiracy.\nI Eye Witne^ies.\n1 It Is further learned on dependable\nauthority that the State exi\npects to show that an official of\nthe United Mine Workers of America\nwas on the ground with a weapon\nin his hand and was acting as an\nadviser. This man has not been\ni indicted.\nEye witnesses will be called bv\nthe State In an effort to prove that\nAlbert Felts \"did not and could not\nhave fired the first shot.'\nOne of these. Dr. Hill, testified to\nthis effect yesterday, and his crMiexamination\n'by J. J. Coniff. for The\ndefense, will be the feature of to,\nmorrow's forenoon sessfon.\nAmong the things the State says\nit expects to prove is that Albert\nFelts had on his person a much\nlarger sum of money than was\n1 turned in at the sheriff's oflce.\n'Committee Prepares\nFirst Deficiency Bill\n1 Conferees from the Appropriations\ncommittees of the House anil Senate\nspent several hours yesterday\ndebating the first deficiency approi\npriation bill for 1921. It is expected\nthat it will be reported to the\nHouse today and be passed in record\ntime.\nThe bill originally provided for\nappropriations for deficiencies to\ngovernment departments in excess\nof $300,000,000, but was pruned to\n$275,918,878 before It passed the\nSenate on Friday.\nMembers of the committee stated\nthat every effort will be made to\nhasten passage of the important\nappropriation bills before the expiration\nof the present Congresi on\nMarch 4.\nit By Accident\na wis hb way late <t\\E -V/?\nof a treat people. X V V'EI\nyears I hare givea eO V*\nthe beat Is Des- X\nLaata?it Beat. far. Hf\nVrM\ntoe* at yoar /AM e\ny. violet Ray. Oal- I AS\n^,r\"n: rr,. V\nppllaacaa that leasee\nParaaeat te ft.w. Kxaaalaatlaa\n?aM la A?tfs4as?.\nPfcaae N. 5247.\n^ol;' FUIm ft\nGald $1.00\n1^9 Mrer 50c\nDSgJ Urn. 50c\n22-k ctowbj ud\nmove Bridie*\n$3, fTS $S\nL437-441 7th 8t. N.W.\nExpert DestlM, ywmru9 expeHgenre.\nOpes Snn?la>M W A. M. ts\nr 4 P. W. Other bmmrm. 9 A. M. Is\n8 P. M. TcsHsmsUIi ss Kf?es(.\n>s?ResMSiber the sssic address\n?J\nt\nIPHOLDSJAP\nBRITISH SAY,\nOF PACT PAPERS\nmerica Without Valid\nonden^ Heart. i\ni\nof President Wilson and other\nmembers of the council, entrusted\nto 8ir Maurice. By a further agreement\nof the council these minute*\nwere to be kept secret excepting to\nthose members of the council who\nwere present when the Islsnd of\nYap was discussed.\nMiates Examined.\nWhen President Wilson recently\ncontested the Japanese right to this\nisland the minutes in Hankey's possession\nwere examined and It was\ndiscovered that there was no record\nwhatever of Wilson's reservation.\nAs a result of this examination.\nJapan now maintains that the disposition\nof Yap is an accomplished\nfact and that, therefore. Mr. Wilson's\ndesire to have the communica\ntlons congress determine the status\nof Yap and the disposal of cable\nrights cannot be considered.\nI understand the State Department\nhas been, or will be shortly\ninformed of this and that in the\nopinion of England. France and\nItaly, Japan's claims to Yap cannot\n\"now be contested by the American\ngovernment. In other words Japan\nconsiders the Incident closed and\nwill rest her case upon the official\nminutes of the conference guarded\nby Hankey which may be examined\nat any time by President Wilson.\nRefaae to Arield.\nI am informed officially that Ja'\npan has made no proposals to tho\nUnited States that she would ,yield\nto the American objections on condition\nthat Great Britain allow\nequal rights for Japanese nationals\nin the southern Pacific islands. nqw\nunder the mandate of Australia snd\nNew Zealand. Furthermore. Japan\ndoes not Intend to make any such\nproposals because 8lr Hankey's official\nrecords establish fully Japan's\nrights to Yap.\n(Cepyrigkt, lttl, Public Lcdf?r Co.)\nBritish Claims Regarded\nAs Not Material Here\nThe report that Japan's claim to\nthe island of Yap has been substantiated\nto the satisfaction of\nGreat Britain by an official report\nof a Big Four meeting at the Peace\nConference kept secret until now Is\nnot likely to change President\nWilson's contention that there was\nan understanding to \"internationalize\"\nthe Island.\nAlthough recent testimony before\nthe Senate Foreign Relation Committee\ngiven by Norman K. Davis,\nUndersecretary *of' State, revealed\nthe United States to be without\n\"black and white\" proof of the existence\nof such an understanding,\nthe Wilson administration will continue\nto press its point until it goes\nout of office.\nThe exclusive Japanese claim to\nYap as a communications point Is\nbeing disputed by the President i\nand his State Department upon\nwider grounds than the mere question\nof the Peace Conference minute*\nBELGIAN BOY GETS\nHOME IN AMERICA\nWoman Colonel's Heart Won\nBy Sobs of Stowaway\nWar Mascot.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 20.?Monsieur\nMike Gilhooley wiggled into these\nUnited States, so why not Osman\nLouis? Anyway Osman is with us.\nLike Gilhooley, he is a youthful\nBelgian stowaway and it was necessary\nfor him to find a guardian\nangel before the ponderous deportation\nmachinery could be switched\noff.\nLady Bountiful in the plight of\nOsman is Col. Helen Bastedo. who\nwon distinction during war time?\nas head of the woman's motor corps.\nShe heard Osman wail on a ferry\nboat at Ellis Island; heard his story;\nhow he had been a mascot for the\nFirst Division of the American Expeditionary\nForce and had been\nwith the Americans in several battles.\nwas attracted by the frankness\nof the boy and prevailed upon the\nImmigration authorities for a rehearing.\nThis granted, she announced her\nintention of adopting the waif and\neducating him with her three children.\n\"Bless you both,\" said the\nDepartment of Labor afltl today Osman,\nwho is IS, set foot on solid\nAmerican soil.\nCol. Bastedo now holds a dollar-ayear\njob with the Immigration Service\nas director of social welfare on\nEllis Island and it was while making\nan inspection that she heard\nOsman sob about not wanting to go\nback to Belgium wh'sre nobody\nwanted him.\nElectricity Proves\nAble to Run Ship\nNEW YORK. Pelf. 20.?Electricity's\nInitial test in the American merchant\nmarine?the sea voyage of\nthe country's first electrically propelled\ncargo boat?has been proven\na success.\nThis Is Indicated In a letter Just\nreceived in New York by the General\nElectric Company from an engineer\nwho accompanied the. steamship\nEclipse on the first leg of her\nround-the-world Journey. The\nEclipse left New York about December\n1.\nHe reports the Eclipse at Port\nSaid, having covered the first 5.000\nmiles of her especial trip without\na single' atop, through heavy sea*,\nmaintaining good speed and with\na low grade of fuel oil.\nWhite Tuxedo Is Latest\nN. Y. Tailort? Confection\nNEW YORK, Fejt. 20.?'The tailors\nhave been thinking and thlnklng-*-now\nfinally thev have\" hought\nof a new one?the white tuxedo.\nThe New York Cutters' Cfub has\nannounced that its fashion show at\nHotel Commodore March 1 and 2\nwill be featured by the display ot\nwhite tuxedos This style will be\nadapted to spring and summer wear,\nso they say. and will be of serge or\ngabardine.\nThe waistcoat will he nf the same\nmaterial as the rest nf the suit and\nwill hav* the more Informal V\nshape bosom onenlng Instead of\nthe usual U shape.\n\nCHAMBER REPORT\nTELLS OF BETTER\nBUSINESS TRENDS\nSalesmen Find Improved\nCondition in All Parts\nOf Country.\nBusiness condition* will Improve\nfrom now on. says Archer Wall\nDouglas, chairman of the committee\nof statistics and standards of the\nChamber of Commerce of the United\nStates. In his monthly review of\nbusiness. Issued yesterday.\nThe most convincing evidence\nthat ~*-e are on the high road to\ntacovery,\" Douglas says, \"Is found\nIn the universal report, brought by\ntraveling salesmen from every aectlon\nof the country, of steadily\ngrowing sentiment that 'business\nwill be better\" In the spring'?not a\nsudden return to prosperity.' which\nIs neither likely nor desirable, but\na slow and natural working out of\nthose processes of liquidation which\nare now In full operation.\n\"There are few who are more rebponslble\nthan these traveling salesmen\nfor the growth of this healthy\nsentiment, which. In effect, is the\nrecognition of the inherent soundness\nof tk* situation, and that the\nremedies for It lie largely In constructive-action.\nNot only is sentiment\nImproved, but there Ts definite\nincrease In the volume of business\ndone. Farmer* are gradually bringing\ntheir produce to market. Bankers\nare slowly loosening up' and\nextending to farmers and dealers\nmoney and credit, the two vital\nfactors needed to restore the situation.\n\"Despite the general story of farmers\nwithholding their products,\nthere Is daily a steady stream of\ngrain and livestock coming to market,\nnot In full volume, but enough\nto assist In alleviating the situation.\nShipments of early fruits and\nvegetables from California and the\nSouth are running heavily.\nAMUSEMENTS.\nFree Lecture\n?ON?\nCHRISTIAN SCIENCE\nBy Bickaell Younj, C S. of\nChicago, DL\nMember of The Board of Lectureship\nof The Mother Church.\nThe First Church of Christ, Scientist.\nJn Boston. Massachusetts.\nAT FIRST CHBRCH OF CHRIST,\nSCIENTIST.\nCcisaku load tad Zaellrf St. W.\nMonday, Feb. 21, at 8 P. M.\nUnder, the Auspices of\nFirst Church of Christ. Scientist,\nof Washington. D. C.\nNo Collection AH Welcome\n~???A\nMHTOL TKITEIRSS\nI SaOKIJfO PBRMITTKD\nI Today ZilS?'Toalght gtis\nI UlToVn BIB SENSATION\nJ Utt (Wctoyl Lmi?Jlan Lit I\nIN. Y. SYMPHONY\nORCHESTRA\nWALTER DAMROSCH. Conductor\nRACHMANINOFF\nSOLOIST\nTkwwlay, February 24, 4:30\nf-_Art>T laog c at. .V, W.\nTHE SHMrcE\nI ETHI\nA Great Cast\namusements.\nI HI III! ||MM\nI PalacE\nH ?'^\"\"k ?.?H m.\nTQ6AT AMD ALL WEEK\nH M^tro Prewata\ne ina\ni claire\nTt* ?*wl?rkla? St., |ta(t\nla Her Gre